00:10:34.290 --> 00:10:38.600
across the United States in
the last several decades.

00:10:38.600 --> 00:10:40.950
And the third is the fact, this
is a little bit more minor,

00:10:40.950 --> 00:10:43.360
that the House of Representatives
starts each day

00:10:43.360 --> 00:10:45.680
with the Pledge of Allegiance.

00:10:45.680 --> 00:10:47.880
Now the reason why I
start with these three is

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:49.210
because they have something
in common.

00:10:49.210 --> 00:10:51.720
It's not that they have
a president behind them.

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:53.020
It's not that a majority party

00:10:53.020 --> 00:10:54.930
in the House and/or
Senate were behind them.

00:10:54.930 --> 00:10:58.580
But that they took place in
part because of the initiatives

00:10:58.580 --> 00:11:00.670
and efforts of members
of the minority party

00:11:00.670 --> 00:11:02.180
of the House of Representatives.

00:11:02.180 --> 00:11:09.350 position:56%
The Reagan budget got its start with
tax reduction proposal introduced

00:11:09.350 --> 00:11:12.710
by then Congressman Jack Kemp, a
Republican from New York who was

00:11:12.710 --> 00:11:15.520
in the minority, along with
Senator Roth from Delaware.

00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:20.530 position:56%
BRAC got its start with an amendment
that was proposed by then minority,

00:11:20.530 --> 00:11:22.870
member of the minority
Dick Armey of Texas.

00:11:22.870 --> 00:11:29.470 position:56%
And the Pledge of Allegiance got its
start during the 1988 presidential

00:11:29.470 --> 00:11:34.460
campaign when the issue of the
constitutionality of the Pledge

00:11:34.460 --> 00:11:37.040
of Allegiance became an issue with,

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:39.490
there was a bill the
Dukakis had vetoed.

00:11:39.490 --> 00:11:41.420
So Bush was saying
what's your problem

00:11:41.420 --> 00:11:42.720
with the Pledge of Allegiance.

00:11:42.720 --> 00:11:44.840 position:56%
So House Republicans started
saying, we should require the Pledge

00:11:44.840 --> 00:11:47.240
of Allegiance when the House meets.

00:11:47.240 --> 00:11:50.340
And Democrats tried to sort of
hold them off but ultimately agreed

00:11:50.340 --> 00:11:52.120
to do it at least informally.

00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:55.840
So these are examples of ways
in which we had policy changes

00:11:55.840 --> 00:11:59.120
or procedural changes
because of the minority party

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:00.810
in the House of Representatives.

00:12:00.810 --> 00:12:02.720
Now I think this is important
for a number of reasons.

00:12:02.720 --> 00:12:05.350
One is that the conventional
wisdom is that the minority party

00:12:05.350 --> 00:12:08.240
in the House doesn't really matter.

00:12:08.240 --> 00:12:11.170
If you have to be in the minority,
it's the Senate where you want

00:12:11.170 --> 00:12:13.150
to be, not the House
of Representatives.

00:12:13.150 --> 00:12:15.110
It's a majoritarian institution.

00:12:15.110 --> 00:12:16.500
The majority sets the rules.

00:12:16.500 --> 00:12:19.410
And the majority sets
the agenda, etcetera.

00:12:19.410 --> 00:12:22.120
The other thing too, which is what
got me interested in this as well,

00:12:22.120 --> 00:12:25.700
is not just contributions to
policy and procedure by members

00:12:25.700 --> 00:12:29.570
of the minority, but that even when
the minority party doesn't seem

00:12:29.570 --> 00:12:31.670
to have much influence,
it still is active.

00:12:31.670 --> 00:12:33.960
It doesn't give up.

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:37.740
And that got me thinking about why
minority parties do what they do.

00:12:37.740 --> 00:12:41.060
There were a couple actually
specific incidences in recent years

00:12:41.060 --> 00:12:43.760
that piqued my curiosity.

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:48.500
One was the frequent use by the
minority Democrats in the 1990s

00:12:48.500 --> 00:12:51.890
