00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:35.510
But I don't have a
definitive answer.

00:14:35.510 --> 00:14:37.380
It's very hard to draw
causal connections

00:14:37.380 --> 00:14:40.250
between the things a
party does in the minority

00:14:40.250 --> 00:14:43.480
and the political outcomes
that they may be seeking.

00:14:43.480 --> 00:14:46.900 position:56%
Alright, well let me start actually,
and I'll just go back just a second,

00:14:46.900 --> 00:14:48.410
the order in which I'm going
to tackle these questions.

00:14:48.410 --> 00:14:50.000
I'm going to start with number two,

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.680
talk about why the minority
party does what it does.

00:14:52.680 --> 00:14:55.150
Then I'll talk about what
the minority party does.

00:14:55.150 --> 00:14:56.720
And I'll give some examples.

00:14:56.720 --> 00:14:59.020
The book is chocked full of
these things that they do.

00:14:59.020 --> 00:15:01.020
And I'm not going to
talk about all of them.

00:15:01.020 --> 00:15:04.600
And then I will, in doing so,
talk a little bit about four

00:15:04.600 --> 00:15:08.490
and maybe touch on three at
the end, time permitting.

00:15:08.490 --> 00:15:12.010
And I should mention one other
thing too about the presentation.

00:15:12.010 --> 00:15:13.580
You're going to see some graphs.

00:15:13.580 --> 00:15:15.300
You're going to see some tables.

00:15:15.300 --> 00:15:19.320
But this book is I would
say relatively unusual

00:15:19.320 --> 00:15:22.340
for a political science book,
particularly about Congress.

00:15:22.340 --> 00:15:25.440
There's no formal models,
no mathematical models.

00:15:25.440 --> 00:15:29.210
There's not a single regression
equation in it anywhere.

00:15:29.210 --> 00:15:34.880
My purpose was to make it
readable and interesting.

00:15:34.880 --> 00:15:37.560
And, you know, so I
hope I succeeded.

00:15:37.560 --> 00:15:40.780
Okay. So let me start by talking
about what the minority party,

00:15:40.780 --> 00:15:43.060
why the minority party
does what it does.

00:15:43.060 --> 00:15:46.840
Well the obvious and most important
thing to a minority party is

00:15:46.840 --> 00:15:49.190
to not be a minority anymore.

00:15:49.190 --> 00:15:52.720
It is not fun to be in the minority
in the House of Representatives.

00:15:52.720 --> 00:15:57.310
So their primary goal is to
be a majority, to win seats,

00:15:57.310 --> 00:16:00.780
to win seats from the majority
and to be a majority party again.

00:16:00.780 --> 00:16:03.980
Now, the conventional
wisdom would stop there.

00:16:03.980 --> 00:16:06.080
That's what the minority
cares about.

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:08.540
But what I argue in the book
is that that's incomplete.

00:16:08.540 --> 00:16:11.000
That doesn't help us
explain things that they do.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:14.790
They may be out of the public eye,
or they are relevant to voters.

00:16:14.790 --> 00:16:16.090
Other things going on there.

00:16:16.090 --> 00:16:19.680
So there's three other
important collective goals

00:16:19.680 --> 00:16:21.010
to the minority party I argue.

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:22.600
The second is a policy.

00:16:22.600 --> 00:16:24.100
Because even though
they're in the minority,

00:16:24.100 --> 00:16:26.300
members of the minority
party are law makers.

00:16:26.300 --> 00:16:27.730
They want to make the law.

00:16:27.730 --> 00:16:29.730
They want to influence legislation.

00:16:29.730 --> 00:16:32.880
And so to the extent that they
can do that, it's important

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:34.940
to the party collectively.

00:16:34.940 --> 00:16:38.270
The third important goal of the
minority party is the protection

00:16:38.270 --> 00:16:40.130
of its procedural rights.

00:16:40.130 --> 00:16:43.330
Now for the most part, these
rights are a necessary precondition

00:16:43.330 --> 00:16:44.630
to do other things.

00:16:44.630 --> 00:16:46.850
You've got to have
certain powers in order

00:16:46.850 --> 00:16:49.050
to influence policy for instance.

00:16:49.050 --> 00:16:51.770
But I argue that these
rights are also important

00:16:51.770 --> 00:16:53.650
to the minority in
and of themselves.

00:16:53.650 --> 00:16:55.240
They're especially sensitive to it

00:16:55.240 --> 00:16:57.910
because they have fewer
rights under the rules.

00:16:57.910 --> 00:17:00.460
And so they want to protect the
prerogatives that they have.

00:17:00.460 --> 00:17:02.770
And they can get quite
passionate about it if they feel

00:17:02.770 --> 00:17:07.160 position:56%
that those rights are being violated
or their powers are being mitigated.

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:08.940
And the fourth thing that matters

00:17:08.940 --> 00:17:11.520
to the minority is a
successful presidential party.

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:14.140
Now this matters to the
majority party too, of course.

00:17:14.140 --> 00:17:17.570
But especially to the
minority because you want

00:17:17.570 --> 00:17:20.100
to have some allies somewhere
in the national government

00:17:20.100 --> 00:17:23.070
who can help you, can carry
out your policy goals.

00:17:23.070 --> 00:17:26.060
If you are in the so-called deep
minority, so you don't have,

00:17:26.060 --> 00:17:28.490
your party does not have the
Senate or the White House,

00:17:28.490 --> 00:17:30.500
then you are truly powerless.

00:17:30.500 --> 00:17:33.460
So I argue these are four very
important things to the minority.

00:17:33.460 --> 00:17:37.950 position:56%
Now an important thing to note here,
these aren't all equally important.

00:17:37.950 --> 00:17:39.930
Most of the time this
is in the order

00:17:39.930 --> 00:17:41.830
in which they matter
to a minority party.

00:17:41.830 --> 00:17:44.990
But it will also vary
by circumstances.

00:17:44.990 --> 00:17:49.090
So in the 1970s, for instance,
many House Republicans saw no way

00:17:49.090 --> 00:17:50.390
to get into the majority.

00:17:50.390 --> 00:17:52.270
They just could not
see a way to do it.

00:17:52.270 --> 00:17:56.480
So for many of them, the second
goal was the primary goal.

00:17:56.480 --> 00:17:57.940 position:56%
Well if we can't win back the House,

00:17:57.940 --> 00:18:00.300
let's at least try
to influence policy.

00:18:00.300 --> 00:18:03.550
And this became a major conflict
when Newt Gingrich was elected

00:18:03.550 --> 00:18:06.340
to the House because he was
trying to convince the party

00:18:06.340 --> 00:18:09.420
that majority status should
be number one versus others

00:18:09.420 --> 00:18:11.390 position:56%
who were there saying, that's silly.

00:18:11.390 --> 00:18:13.300
We should be number two.

00:18:13.300 --> 00:18:18.010
One other thing I want to note
before I talk about some things

00:18:18.010 --> 00:18:21.120
in particular that the
minority party does.

00:18:21.120 --> 00:18:24.380
That table, it's sort of a,
kind of what you might call

00:18:24.380 --> 00:18:26.690
in political science a
rational choice approach.

00:18:26.690 --> 00:18:29.650
So the idea is that the
party is calculating.

00:18:29.650 --> 00:18:31.380
They think about what
matters most to them.

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:33.450 position:56%
And they figure out how to get them.

00:18:33.450 --> 00:18:36.460
Well something that's important
that I discovered in my interviews

00:18:36.460 --> 00:18:38.970
that I did for this book
and other research is

00:18:38.970 --> 00:18:41.690
that that's a little simplistic.

00:18:41.690 --> 00:18:43.360
That other things matter
as the minority too.

00:18:43.360 --> 00:18:45.690
And I open the book
with these two quotes.

00:18:45.690 --> 00:18:47.710
And I highlight two key words there

00:18:47.710 --> 00:18:52.490
to underscore an important common
sense that the minority party has.

00:18:52.490 --> 00:18:55.880
Frustration and freedom.

00:18:55.880 --> 00:18:59.180
So on the one hand it's very
frustrating to be in the minority

00:18:59.180 --> 00:19:01.470
and to lose over and
over and over again.

00:19:01.470 --> 00:19:03.220
On the other hand, you
have no obligations.

00:19:03.220 --> 00:19:04.520
You're not governing.

00:19:04.520 --> 00:19:05.820
You can do what you like.

00:19:05.820 --> 00:19:09.590
And so because these are two
important characteristics of life

00:19:09.590 --> 00:19:11.390
in the minority, there's
some consequences

00:19:11.390 --> 00:19:13.990
to how a minority party behaves.

00:19:13.990 --> 00:19:18.050 position:56%
Morale. Morale is very hard to keep.

00:19:18.050 --> 00:19:20.200
It's very hard to keep good morale
when you're in the minority.

00:19:20.200 --> 00:19:24.350
And it's a constant struggle
for leaders to keep the morale

00:19:24.350 --> 00:19:26.660
of their fellow partisans high.

00:19:26.660 --> 00:19:28.880
If you can't, they may leave.

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:32.380
They may not cooperate or work with
the party on things that they need.

00:19:32.380 --> 00:19:35.510
So this is often a sort
of an underlying theme

00:19:35.510 --> 00:19:39.700
of minority party politics is
keeping people's morale high.

00:19:39.700 --> 00:19:41.040
Emotion also matters.

00:19:41.040 --> 00:19:44.230
Sometimes the majority does
something that's so infuriating

00:19:44.230 --> 00:19:47.340
to the minority that they
just do something, alright.

00:19:47.340 --> 00:19:49.980
They stage a protest,
or they try something.

00:19:49.980 --> 00:19:52.320
More out of anger and
frustration than out

00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:55.500
of a calculate analysis
of what will work.

00:19:55.500 --> 00:19:58.120
And then also action
is its own reward.

00:19:58.120 --> 00:20:00.600
A couple of folks I talked
to said that, you know,

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:04.610
leaders felt the need
to do something.

00:20:04.610 --> 00:20:06.970
You got to show the troops
that you're doing something,

00:20:06.970 --> 00:20:09.330
even if it's not going
to bring you back

00:20:09.330 --> 00:20:11.170
into the majority any time soon.

00:20:11.170 --> 00:20:13.300
And that can be inherently
rewarding,

00:20:13.300 --> 00:20:14.600 position:56%
and there are certainly some members

00:20:14.600 --> 00:20:17.210
of the minority who
just like the fight.

00:20:17.210 --> 00:20:20.060
They just enjoy the
battle for its own sake.

00:20:20.060 --> 00:20:21.630
And then uncertainty.

00:20:21.630 --> 00:20:22.930
So there's a lot of uncertainty.

00:20:22.930 --> 00:20:26.110
Sometimes the people in the
minority just try things.

00:20:26.110 --> 00:20:27.600
They don't know if it's
going to work or not.

00:20:27.600 --> 00:20:29.760
If it doesn't, it probably
won't make a difference.

00:20:29.760 --> 00:20:31.920
So these are four important
themes of the book,

00:20:31.920 --> 00:20:34.500
or sort of late motifs of the book.

00:20:34.500 --> 00:20:38.810
Okay, what I'd like to
do now is talk about each

00:20:38.810 --> 00:20:43.010
of these four categories of tactics
that the minority party uses.

00:20:43.010 --> 00:20:45.710
Now here on the slide I
show all of the things

00:20:45.710 --> 00:20:47.460
that I discuss under each headline.

00:20:47.460 --> 00:20:50.270
I'm not going to talk about all
of those in my presentation.

00:20:50.270 --> 00:20:52.850
I'm going to highlight
one as an example for each

00:20:52.850 --> 00:20:54.430
of these four categories.

00:20:54.430 --> 00:20:59.400
So electioneering, messaging,
obstructing and legislating.

00:20:59.400 --> 00:21:02.790
Let me start with electioneering.

00:21:02.790 --> 00:21:07.080
And the example I want to give is
the use, by really both parties,

00:21:07.080 --> 00:21:12.930
of a technique to identify
strong candidates and help them

00:21:12.930 --> 00:21:15.280
with training and fundraising.

00:21:15.280 --> 00:21:16.880
So this is one way
a minority can try

00:21:16.880 --> 00:21:19.390
to get back the majority
is find people running,

00:21:19.390 --> 00:21:21.320
particularly if they're
running against incumbents

00:21:21.320 --> 00:21:24.070
in the other party and
say, you're promising.

00:21:24.070 --> 00:21:27.670
We're going to help you raise
more money and help you succeed.

00:21:27.670 --> 00:21:31.350
So these are, for instance,
the red to blue program

00:21:31.350 --> 00:21:33.880
that the Democrats
started in the early 2000s.

00:21:33.880 --> 00:21:37.730
And the young guns program the
Republicans started in 2010.

00:21:37.730 --> 00:21:40.190
And they've been fairly successful.

00:21:40.190 --> 00:21:44.760 position:56%
So, you know, Kirsten Gillibrand was
elected as a red to blue in 2006.

00:21:44.760 --> 00:21:48.310
Allen West from Florida was
elected in the young guns program.

00:21:48.310 --> 00:21:52.650
But what I want to talk about is
not whether it led to Democrats

00:21:52.650 --> 00:21:55.640
or Republicans winning
but a more immediate goal.

00:21:55.640 --> 00:21:58.220
Did it actually help these
candidates raise more money?

00:21:58.220 --> 00:21:59.850
Was it successful?

00:21:59.850 --> 00:22:02.820
So let me just show
one example of this.

00:22:02.820 --> 00:22:05.970
I've got more examples in the book.

00:22:05.970 --> 00:22:07.850
This is early 2006.

00:22:07.850 --> 00:22:10.500
This is the year the
Democrats retake the House.

00:22:10.500 --> 00:22:14.430
And the red to blue program is
targeting a number of Democrats

00:22:14.430 --> 00:22:15.730
that they find promising.

00:22:15.730 --> 00:22:20.350
So what I have here on the table,
the blue are Democrats running

00:22:20.350 --> 00:22:25.160
who get put into or accepted
into the red to blue program.

00:22:25.160 --> 00:22:29.380
And the first set of bars
are before they are put

00:22:29.380 --> 00:22:31.680
in the program or allowed in.

00:22:31.680 --> 00:22:34.820
And then the second
set are afterwards.

00:22:34.820 --> 00:22:37.710
And I compare each of those
red to blue candidates

00:22:37.710 --> 00:22:41.590
with another Democrat running from
a similar district who has showed

00:22:41.590 --> 00:22:44.160
at least some degree
of fundraising acumen.

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:48.870
So not extremely minor
candidates but fairly strong ones.

00:22:48.870 --> 00:22:51.190
The first thing to see, of course,
is that you don't get into the red

00:22:51.190 --> 00:22:54.280
to blue program unless you're
already good at raising money.

00:22:54.280 --> 00:22:56.050
That shouldn't be a surprise.

00:22:56.050 --> 00:22:59.760
But, what I show here, and I also
show elsewhere in the book is

00:22:59.760 --> 00:23:03.110
that after they're in one of
these programs like red to blue,

00:23:03.110 --> 00:23:07.180
these candidates do better
at raising money than those

00:23:07.180 --> 00:23:09.000
who are not in the program.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:11.240
In this case, the red to
blue candidates raised

00:23:11.240 --> 00:23:15.160
about $120,000 collectively over
and above what they had raised

00:23:15.160 --> 00:23:18.890
in the first quarter of 2006,
whereas the matched pairs,

00:23:18.890 --> 00:23:22.200
the ones in red, only raised
about half that much, 60,000.

00:23:22.200 --> 00:23:25.740
So it's an example of ways in
which the minority party tries

00:23:25.740 --> 00:23:27.040
to win seats.

00:23:27.040 --> 00:23:28.810
And of course, again, the
majority party does this

00:23:28.810 --> 00:23:30.410
as well you should know.

00:23:30.410 --> 00:23:33.730
Alright, next I want to
talk about messaging.

00:23:33.730 --> 00:23:38.410
Messaging is something that you
see all the time in Congress.

00:23:38.410 --> 00:23:42.800
And it's something that is
particularly emphasized,

00:23:42.800 --> 00:23:45.760
or at least has been
recently by minority parties.

00:23:45.760 --> 00:23:50.530 position:56%
So John Boehner, for instance, after
Republicans lost the house in 2006,

00:23:50.530 --> 00:23:52.890
was quoted as saying, you know,

00:23:52.890 --> 00:23:55.050
we have to forget that
we're legislators.

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:57.340
But we can be communicators.

00:23:57.340 --> 00:23:59.170
That's what we have to do.

00:23:59.170 --> 00:24:00.470
And both parties when they're

00:24:00.470 --> 00:24:04.480
in the minority have emphasized
communication and messaging.

00:24:04.480 --> 00:24:07.050
So there's all kinds of ways that
you can get your message out.

00:24:07.050 --> 00:24:11.280
And what I want to talk about today
is just one kind of messaging tool

00:24:11.280 --> 00:24:13.350 position:56%
which are one-minute floor speeches.

00:24:13.350 --> 00:24:16.050
So this is at the beginning
of each session when a number

00:24:16.050 --> 00:24:19.900 position:56%
of members prepared to give their
speeches, they ask unanimous consent

00:24:19.900 --> 00:24:21.880
to address the floor for one
minute, and they can talk

00:24:21.880 --> 00:24:24.090
about really whatever they want.

00:24:24.090 --> 00:24:25.390
Although, as I discuss in the book,

00:24:25.390 --> 00:24:29.980
it's becoming increasingly the
party agenda what they talk about.

00:24:29.980 --> 00:24:33.150
So I usually, I like to have one
Democrat and one Republican here,

00:24:33.150 --> 00:24:34.450
but I couldn't help myself.

00:24:34.450 --> 00:24:37.250
I had to put Jim Traficant
on this because he was

00:24:37.250 --> 00:24:39.510
such a colorful speaker
in his one minute,

00:24:39.510 --> 00:24:42.240
both in them majority
and in the minority.

00:24:42.240 --> 00:24:47.130
So what I do in the book
is I look at whether

00:24:47.130 --> 00:24:50.010
or not these things might
influence public opinion.

00:24:50.010 --> 00:24:52.850 position:56%
I mean messaging can have all kinds
of effects that are hard to measure.

00:24:52.850 --> 00:24:58.380
But one immediate possible effect
would be does it move the public

00:24:58.380 --> 00:25:01.190
in the direction that
the party wants it to?

00:25:01.190 --> 00:25:05.220
So I looked at, there's so
many of these one minutes,

00:25:05.220 --> 00:25:06.520
and I could not code them all.

00:25:06.520 --> 00:25:09.550
So I took samples every five
years and coded them for content.

00:25:09.550 --> 00:25:13.490 position:56%
And then I'll talk about a case
study involving really a sort of use

00:25:13.490 --> 00:25:15.110
of these and whether
it moves the public

00:25:15.110 --> 00:25:17.640
in the direction that
the party wanted.

00:25:18.660 --> 00:25:23.070
So this is a chart that shows
the percent of one minute given

00:25:23.070 --> 00:25:25.890
by the minority and majority party
that talked about the president

00:25:25.890 --> 00:25:28.750
or the presidential candidate.

00:25:28.750 --> 00:25:30.570
The circles are the majority party.

00:25:30.570 --> 00:25:33.330
The squares are the minority party.

00:25:33.330 --> 00:25:35.490
In addition, if they're hollow,

00:25:35.490 --> 00:25:39.330
it means that the party does
not control the White House.

00:25:39.330 --> 00:25:42.800
So it's the opposite party
that's in the White House.

00:25:42.800 --> 00:25:46.450
And what I found, I sort of thought
well maybe the minority would be

00:25:46.450 --> 00:25:48.200
biased towards the president
or something like that.

00:25:48.200 --> 00:25:50.780
What I actually found is both
parties care about the president,

00:25:50.780 --> 00:25:54.070
but really only when the
president is of the opposite party.

00:25:54.070 --> 00:25:55.860
That's when you see
a larger percentage

00:25:55.860 --> 00:25:58.410
of their one minutes
talking about the president.

00:25:58.410 --> 00:26:02.390
So, for instance, in 1990, for
example, I want to say 1985.

00:26:02.390 --> 00:26:05.160
It doesn't really matter,
1985, the Republicans are

00:26:05.160 --> 00:26:08.480
in the minority, and
Reagan is president.

00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:10.470
But it's the majority
party, Democrats,

00:26:10.470 --> 00:26:12.480
that are talking about
the president.

00:26:12.480 --> 00:26:15.460
So there's a way in which both
parties sort of see their roles

00:26:15.460 --> 00:26:18.340
as oppositional in their messaging
with respect to the president,

00:26:18.340 --> 00:26:20.490
depending on who that president is.

00:26:20.490 --> 00:26:22.200
There is, however, a
definite difference

00:26:22.200 --> 00:26:25.520
between the majority/minority
party on partisanship.

00:26:25.520 --> 00:26:28.890
The majority tends to talk more
about party and partisanship

00:26:28.890 --> 00:26:31.160
than the majority party does.

00:26:31.160 --> 00:26:35.200
And, and here's where one of those
other collectively goals comes

00:26:35.200 --> 00:26:36.500
into play.

00:26:36.500 --> 00:26:38.470
The minority talks a
lot more about procedure

00:26:38.470 --> 00:26:40.220
than the majority does
in their one minute.

00:26:40.220 --> 00:26:42.110
Now they don't talk
that much about it.

00:26:42.110 --> 00:26:46.080
No more than about 5 1/2 % of their
one minutes are on that subject.

00:26:46.080 --> 00:26:48.340
But that's something that
also matters to the minority.

00:26:48.340 --> 00:26:50.170
It's procedure and how
the House is working.

00:26:50.170 --> 00:26:53.860
And most of these speeches
are, unsurprisingly,

00:26:53.860 --> 00:26:55.630
complaining about procedure

00:26:55.630 --> 00:26:59.150
and the way it's being
misused by the majority party.

00:26:59.150 --> 00:27:02.110
So do these have any effects?

00:27:02.110 --> 00:27:04.540
Well, as I said, what I
do in the book is I look

00:27:04.540 --> 00:27:07.670
at the relationship
with public opinion.

00:27:07.670 --> 00:27:11.810
So let me give a case study
here of a use of one minutes

00:27:11.810 --> 00:27:17.750
by House Republicans in
mid-2009, July, 2009.

00:27:17.750 --> 00:27:21.320
The Republicans decide their
big theme is going to be jobs.

00:27:21.320 --> 00:27:24.520
So they have everybody go to the
floor and give one minute speeches

00:27:24.520 --> 00:27:27.600
and use the same phrase,
where are the jobs?

00:27:27.600 --> 00:27:30.760
They repeat that over
and over and over.

00:27:30.760 --> 00:27:32.060
Where are the jobs?

00:27:32.060 --> 00:27:33.360
Where are the jobs?

00:27:33.360 --> 00:27:35.240
That's in every one-minute
speech practically.

00:27:35.240 --> 00:27:39.850 position:56%
So there's a Republican polling firm
that asked the question of folks,

00:27:39.850 --> 00:27:41.970
what matters most to
you when you're thinking

00:27:41.970 --> 00:27:44.270
about your vote for Congress?

00:27:44.270 --> 00:27:49.340
And they asked this
question in early June, 2009.

00:27:49.340 --> 00:27:53.550
And they found out 37% that
responded said the economy.

00:27:53.550 --> 00:27:56.310
And 5% said jobs.

00:27:56.310 --> 00:28:00.030
After Boehner had the, Majority
Leader Boehner, another Republican,

00:28:00.030 --> 00:28:03.640
had done this where are the jobs,
campaigned the same polling firm,

00:28:03.640 --> 00:28:08.710
asked the same question,
and this was the result.

00:28:08.710 --> 00:28:13.120
Yeah. Exact same percentage
on the economy and 1% increase

00:28:13.120 --> 00:28:17.240
in those same jobs, which of course
is well within the margin of error.

00:28:17.240 --> 00:28:19.160
And I discuss in the
book other cases

00:28:19.160 --> 00:28:22.780
in which you don't see the
public moving as a result

00:28:22.780 --> 00:28:24.080
of these kinds of messaging.

00:28:24.080 --> 00:28:25.950
Now does that mean
messaging doesn't work?

00:28:25.950 --> 00:28:27.410
Not necessarily.

00:28:27.410 --> 00:28:29.370
It could have longer term effects.

00:28:29.370 --> 00:28:31.840
It could also do some of the
things that I talked about earlier.

00:28:31.840 --> 00:28:34.500
It could boost morale for the
party, make some members feel

00:28:34.500 --> 00:28:38.050
like they're doing something to try
to get out of the minority status.

00:28:38.050 --> 00:28:41.560
But if the goal is to move
the needle of the public,

00:28:41.560 --> 00:28:44.420
public opinion, in one
direction, it doesn't seem

00:28:44.420 --> 00:28:46.720
to have much of an effect.

00:28:46.720 --> 00:28:50.330
Okay, third category of tactics
is delaying and obstructing.

00:28:50.330 --> 00:28:51.760
This is one that I,
this is a chapter

00:28:51.760 --> 00:28:54.590
that I particularly enjoyed
writing because it just strikes me

00:28:54.590 --> 00:28:58.070
as peculiar to think about
the minority in the House

00:28:58.070 --> 00:28:59.830
as trying to delay and obstruct.

00:28:59.830 --> 00:29:01.130
This is not the Senate.

00:29:01.130 --> 00:29:02.710
They don't have a filibuster.

00:29:02.710 --> 00:29:05.920
So what kinds of things can
they do to slow things down?

00:29:05.920 --> 00:29:09.670
There are things, in fact, that
they can do to slow things down.

00:29:09.670 --> 00:29:11.840
And I talk in the book about
some notorious examples

00:29:11.840 --> 00:29:13.890
which I can discuss in Q&amp;A later.

00:29:13.890 --> 00:29:19.870
One of my favorites
involved Don Rumsfeld in 1968

00:29:19.870 --> 00:29:21.820
and something that he led.

00:29:21.820 --> 00:29:26.320
But, I'm going to talk
instead today about motions

00:29:26.320 --> 00:29:28.230
to rise and motions to adjourn.

00:29:28.230 --> 00:29:32.740
So these are procedural motions
in the House of Representatives.

00:29:32.740 --> 00:29:35.430
The motion to adjourn is a motion

00:29:35.430 --> 00:29:38.420
to basically end the session,
to be done for the day.

00:29:38.420 --> 00:29:40.880
Motion to rise is if the House
is meeting and the committee

00:29:40.880 --> 00:29:43.270
as a whole to consider amendments.

00:29:43.270 --> 00:29:46.870
And then you rise, this would be to
end that portion of the discussion

00:29:46.870 --> 00:29:49.710
and leave the committee as a whole.

00:29:49.710 --> 00:29:51.700
So I ask two questions in the book.

00:29:51.700 --> 00:29:53.910
One is, why are they being done?

00:29:53.910 --> 00:29:56.590
And second of all, do
they yield results.

00:29:56.590 --> 00:30:00.060
So let me just first show a chart
demonstrating how often these

00:30:00.060 --> 00:30:01.360
are done.

00:30:01.360 --> 00:30:02.660
You can see they were very rare.

00:30:02.660 --> 00:30:04.820
These were done by, this is
minority party motions to rise

00:30:04.820 --> 00:30:06.290
and adjourn I should say.

00:30:06.290 --> 00:30:07.590
Very, very rare.

00:30:07.590 --> 00:30:10.720
Became more popular in the early
90s, really took off a couple

00:30:10.720 --> 00:30:13.340
of key Congresses,
and it sort of died

00:30:13.340 --> 00:30:16.500
down again in terms of popularity.

00:30:16.500 --> 00:30:19.750
These are useful for slowing
things done, not a whole lot

00:30:19.750 --> 00:30:21.660
because you do one,
you have a roll call.

00:30:21.660 --> 00:30:23.220
That takes 15 minutes.

00:30:23.220 --> 00:30:25.700
But sometimes the minority
does them over and over

00:30:25.700 --> 00:30:27.550
and over and over and over again.

00:30:27.550 --> 00:30:30.230
That can slow things
down considerably.

00:30:30.230 --> 00:30:33.730
So what I did for these motions
is I looked to see if the member

00:30:33.730 --> 00:30:36.910
of Congress who offered
them gave an explanation.

00:30:36.910 --> 00:30:38.600
So went to the floor and said,

00:30:38.600 --> 00:30:41.420
you know I'm really mad you
wouldn't let me offer my amendment.

00:30:41.420 --> 00:30:43.090
I move we adjourn.

00:30:43.090 --> 00:30:45.340
Or, it's ridiculous we're
debating gun control.

00:30:45.340 --> 00:30:46.920
We should be debating
something else.

00:30:46.920 --> 00:30:48.920
I move that the committee rise.

00:30:48.920 --> 00:30:51.430
Now only about half of these
motions is there an explanation.

00:30:51.430 --> 00:30:53.890
But of those half,
this is the percentage

00:30:53.890 --> 00:30:56.360
that fall into each category.

00:30:56.360 --> 00:30:59.730
I categorized them based on
the general concern, complaint,

00:30:59.730 --> 00:31:01.330
comment that was being made.

00:31:01.330 --> 00:31:05.060
And just the takeaway point
from this is that some of these,

00:31:05.060 --> 00:31:08.620
yeah they could be explained by the
minority caring about reelection,

00:31:08.620 --> 00:31:11.040
because if you can't
offer your amendment

00:31:11.040 --> 00:31:16.130 position:56%
because of an unfair floor rule,
then you can't get your message out.

00:31:16.130 --> 00:31:19.900
You can't change a bill the way
you want, so also policy concerns.

00:31:19.900 --> 00:31:22.510
But some of these things
are very arcane, you know,

00:31:22.510 --> 00:31:25.710
violation of regular order.

00:31:25.710 --> 00:31:28.030
Some other abusive power.

00:31:28.030 --> 00:31:31.370
And I would hear quote
Robert Michael,

00:31:31.370 --> 00:31:35.040
former Republican minority
leader who called of these kinds

00:31:35.040 --> 00:31:39.430 position:56%
of debates MEGO, my eyes glaze over.

00:31:39.430 --> 00:31:41.100
And this is boring
stuff for most people.

00:31:41.100 --> 00:31:42.980
They don't care about
motions to, they don't care

00:31:42.980 --> 00:31:45.200 position:56%
about the restrictiveness of a rule.

00:31:45.200 --> 00:31:46.500
So here's where it's important

00:31:46.500 --> 00:31:48.510
to understand the minority
caring about how it's treated.

00:31:48.510 --> 00:31:50.810
About its procedural rights.

00:31:50.810 --> 00:31:55.280
And here's something that I
found interesting that it's hard

00:31:55.280 --> 00:31:58.990
to necessarily trace the causal
connection that these motions

00:31:58.990 --> 00:32:02.250 position:56%
to rise are generally used, and then
this change happened as a result.

00:32:02.250 --> 00:32:06.410
But nonetheless, a good percentage
of these were then followed

00:32:06.410 --> 00:32:09.250
by some kind of change,
either a bill being changed

00:32:09.250 --> 00:32:13.430
or amendments being allowed,
or the agenda being altered,

00:32:13.430 --> 00:32:15.060
to help the minority party.

00:32:15.060 --> 00:32:18.600
So this at least suggests
that these can effective.

00:32:18.600 --> 00:32:20.320
Not in the majority of times,

00:32:20.320 --> 00:32:23.080
but they can be effective
in helping the minority.

00:32:23.080 --> 00:32:29.670 position:56%
Alright, the last subject that I
want to talk about, or last category

00:32:29.670 --> 00:32:32.020
of tactics, is legislating.

00:32:32.020 --> 00:32:34.680
So this is one in which I actually
originally wasn't, I wasn't going

00:32:34.680 --> 00:32:36.470
to have this in the book.

00:32:36.470 --> 00:32:39.530
I thought, well the minority
doesn't really legislate that much.

00:32:39.530 --> 00:32:42.570
But the reviewer said you've
got to talk about legislating.

00:32:42.570 --> 00:32:44.670
Surely that, it's Congress,
right, okay.

00:32:44.670 --> 00:32:47.560
So I did. So I added a
chapter about legislating.

00:32:47.560 --> 00:32:51.350
And I look at different ways
the minority can legislate.

00:32:51.350 --> 00:32:53.390
Can influence legislation.

00:32:53.390 --> 00:32:58.460 position:56%
Yes the minority is outnumbered, but
that doesn't mean that it can't win.

00:32:58.460 --> 00:33:02.330
The most common way of measuring if
a minority wins in a floor vote is

00:33:02.330 --> 00:33:03.970
through what's called
a majority roll.

00:33:03.970 --> 00:33:05.540
That's if a majority,
the majority party,

00:33:05.540 --> 00:33:08.880
votes against something,
but it still passes.

00:33:08.880 --> 00:33:12.680
We colloquially call this a
violation of the Hastert Rule.

00:33:12.680 --> 00:33:15.010
And we've seen that
violation a number of times,

00:33:15.010 --> 00:33:18.350
so it's not technically
a rule, more of a norm.

00:33:18.350 --> 00:33:20.030
So we've seen that this can happen,

00:33:20.030 --> 00:33:22.480
and it can happen on
really big bills.

00:33:22.480 --> 00:33:24.900
But a lot of scholars say, well
this doesn't happen that much.

00:33:24.900 --> 00:33:28.020
So really minority doesn't
have that much influence.

00:33:28.020 --> 00:33:30.780
One of the things that I argue in
the book is, besides these happen

00:33:30.780 --> 00:33:32.480
on pretty important things,

00:33:32.480 --> 00:33:34.640
is that there are other
ways the minority wins

00:33:34.640 --> 00:33:36.680
on floor votes besides these rolls.

00:33:36.680 --> 00:33:40.700
So this chart shows
three kinds of votes.

00:33:40.700 --> 00:33:44.990
The blue line shows the percentage
of votes on final passage

00:33:44.990 --> 00:33:47.650
in which the majority was rolled,
a violation of the Hastert Rule.

00:33:47.650 --> 00:33:50.670
So you can see it doesn't
happen very often.

00:33:50.670 --> 00:33:53.850
However, if you include
amendments, that's the red line,

00:33:53.850 --> 00:33:55.840
it does happen more often.

00:33:55.840 --> 00:33:57.760
And then if you look at the times

00:33:57.760 --> 00:34:01.520
that the majority either
loses a bill it wants to pass,

00:34:01.520 --> 00:34:03.570
or a bill passes that
it wants to lose.

00:34:03.570 --> 00:34:06.100
In other words, the majority
votes for it, but it fails.

00:34:06.100 --> 00:34:08.960
The majority votes
against it, or it succeeds.

00:34:08.960 --> 00:34:11.450
You see even more frequently
that happens.

00:34:11.450 --> 00:34:13.180
It's still not that much.

00:34:13.180 --> 00:34:15.900
I mean it's still under 20%.

00:34:15.900 --> 00:34:18.550
The point is that the minority
party can win floor votes,

00:34:18.550 --> 00:34:20.570
and does win floor votes.

00:34:20.570 --> 00:34:22.360
I would note on this chart

00:34:22.360 --> 00:34:26.200
that there might be a slight
downward trend going on there.

00:34:26.200 --> 00:34:28.340
And that's an important
theme of the book.

00:34:28.340 --> 00:34:31.850 position:56%
One of the things that I should have
mentioned is that this is talking

00:34:31.850 --> 00:34:34.720
about the minority party, but
I take a historical approach.

00:34:34.720 --> 00:34:38.780
So I start from 1970 and
