00:34:47.080 --> 00:34:50.700
The minority party cares
about more than just power.

00:34:50.700 --> 00:34:54.850
And its actions, things it does
are at times associate success.

00:34:54.850 --> 00:34:57.530
Not always, but at times.

00:34:57.530 --> 00:34:58.990
But things have changed.

00:34:58.990 --> 00:35:00.290
No doubt about it.

00:35:00.290 --> 00:35:04.940
In 1970 the minority party had
more opportunities to legislate.

00:35:04.940 --> 00:35:08.230
Most, or a majority of
floor rules for the rules

00:35:08.230 --> 00:35:10.420
for considering bills were
open, or largely open,

00:35:10.420 --> 00:35:12.580
so that you could offer amendments.

00:35:12.580 --> 00:35:16.830 position:56%
There was more of a focus on
legislating arguably than messaging.

00:35:16.830 --> 00:35:19.570
What's happened is, for a number
of reasons I discuss in the book,

00:35:19.570 --> 00:35:24.510 position:56%
opportunities for the minority party
to legislate directly have shrunk.

00:35:24.510 --> 00:35:28.180
And so, if you think about a
stream and block that stream,

00:35:28.180 --> 00:35:30.430
the water still has
to flow somewhere.

00:35:30.430 --> 00:35:34.140 position:56%
So the minority party either finds
other ways to influence legislation,

00:35:34.140 --> 00:35:39.020
or it finds other avenues for,
or outlets for its energy.

00:35:39.020 --> 00:35:41.440
And one of the biggest
ones is messaging.

00:35:41.440 --> 00:35:43.030
Messaging is very important.

00:35:43.030 --> 00:35:46.620 position:56%
So now amendments aren't necessarily
offered to influence a bill

00:35:46.620 --> 00:35:49.240
but rather to send a message.

00:35:49.240 --> 00:35:54.180
Roy Blunt, who is, when he was
