So there is a way in which how
many seats you have is not,

00:39:14.230 --> 00:39:15.980
it's necessary, but not
sufficient condition

00:39:15.980 --> 00:39:19.480
to having the mentality you need.

00:39:19.480 --> 00:39:21.210
Yes sir.

00:39:21.210 --> 00:39:29.090
&gt;&gt; I'm particularly struck by your
findings on one minute speeches.

00:39:29.090 --> 00:39:37.150
I'm going to keep that in mind
the next time my boss asks me

00:39:37.150 --> 00:39:40.150
to write one.

00:39:40.150 --> 00:39:51.500
But, I was wondering, in which way
is the minority party has been most

00:39:51.500 --> 00:39:54.110
effective at leveraging the
[inaudible] the narrative.

00:39:54.110 --> 00:39:56.900
Where is the correlation
in the various things?

00:39:56.900 --> 00:40:01.410
Whether it's one minutes
or special orders

00:40:01.410 --> 00:40:02.890
or anything else that [inaudible].

00:40:02.890 --> 00:40:04.450
&gt;&gt; Matt, could you
repeat the question?

00:40:04.450 --> 00:40:05.750
&gt;&gt; Matthew Green: Yes, right.

00:40:05.750 --> 00:40:08.540
So the question is, did I find
any examples or incidences

00:40:08.540 --> 00:40:11.550
in which messaging in
general was most effective.

00:40:11.550 --> 00:40:12.850
Is that correct?

00:40:12.850 --> 00:40:14.150
Well the short answer is in the
contemporary congress, not many.

00:40:14.150 --> 00:40:15.450
The best examples that I
could find are from times

00:40:15.450 --> 00:40:16.750
when new messaging tactics
were first developed.

00:40:16.750 --> 00:40:18.330
So the use of one minutes in a
partisan fashion, which really came

00:40:18.330 --> 00:40:19.920
about in the late 70s,
Republicans started doing it.

00:40:19.920 --> 00:40:21.220
That really, really, Democrats
really didn't know what

00:40:21.220 --> 00:40:22.520
to do about that at first.

00:40:22.520 --> 00:40:23.820
And said why are you so
angry at us and talking

00:40:23.820 --> 00:40:25.120
about Ronald Reagan all the time?

00:40:25.120 --> 00:40:28.410
And then again, Republicans
in the 1993, 94,

00:40:28.410 --> 00:40:30.460
they were still in the minority.

00:40:30.460 --> 00:40:32.940
They had developed, Robert
Michael had developed this in part

00:40:32.940 --> 00:40:36.730
because he was concerned
about Newt Gingrich possibly,

00:40:36.730 --> 00:40:38.030
you know, being so assertive.

00:40:38.030 --> 00:40:39.800
He wanted to show he was
also a leader of the party.

00:40:39.800 --> 00:40:44.980
So he set up a team of Republicans
who would use one minutes.

00:40:44.980 --> 00:40:46.320
But they used them
in a different way.

00:40:46.320 --> 00:40:51.080
They did sort of top ten
lists and catchy song tunes.

00:40:51.080 --> 00:40:55.670 position:56%
And that got the press' attention
more than the previous use had been.

00:40:55.670 --> 00:40:58.990
So there's a way in
which now it's hard

00:40:58.990 --> 00:41:03.140
to see standard messaging
tactics having much of an effect,

00:41:03.140 --> 00:41:04.960
or at least getting much attention.

00:41:04.960 --> 00:41:11.130
But as I argue in the book,
innovation and, well innovation,

00:41:11.130 --> 00:41:13.850
coming up with new ideas,
new ways of doing things,

00:41:13.850 --> 00:41:18.150
can be more effective, at
least in the short run.

00:41:18.150 --> 00:41:19.450
Yes.

00:41:19.450 --> 00:41:20.750
&gt;&gt; Did you look at
the committee process

00:41:20.750 --> 00:41:22.750
and the minority's [inaudible].

00:41:22.750 --> 00:41:25.000
&gt;&gt; Repeat again.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:26.300
&gt;&gt; Matthew Green: Yes.

00:41:26.300 --> 00:41:28.570
Did I look at committees in
the book, and the answer is no.

00:41:28.570 --> 00:41:32.780
I, it was really about, it
was really sort of the scope.

00:41:32.780 --> 00:41:36.750
I had to limit it at some point,
which is a shame because I think

00:41:36.750 --> 00:41:39.540
that itself could be
a whole other book.

00:41:39.540 --> 00:41:41.610
There are, first of
all on the one hand,

00:41:41.610 --> 00:41:44.210
ways in which minority party
members can have more influence

00:41:44.210 --> 00:41:47.660 position:56%
in a committee, depending on who the
chair is and the balance of power

00:41:47.660 --> 00:41:49.970
and what the issues are,
if it's transportation

00:41:49.970 --> 00:41:51.680
versus let's say, judiciary.

00:41:51.680 --> 00:41:56.320
At the same time, some of the best
examples I found of obstruction

00:41:56.320 --> 00:42:00.340 position:56%
and messaging were in committees,
which I just didn't use in the book.

00:42:00.340 --> 00:42:03.930
But so in some ways,
committees can be a model

00:42:03.930 --> 00:42:06.610
for more collaborative
governance and less partisanship.

00:42:06.610 --> 00:42:09.000
On the other hand, they
can be just a microcosm

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:11.600
of the way the House
is as a whole operates.

00:42:11.600 --> 00:42:14.560
But maybe that will
be my next project.

00:42:14.560 --> 00:42:15.860
Yeah.

00:42:15.860 --> 00:42:20.010
&gt;&gt; I can think of a lot of things
to say, which is a compliment.

00:42:20.010 --> 00:42:24.650
But just to limit myself to
maybe one thing that's more

00:42:24.650 --> 00:42:26.950
of a comment than a question.

00:42:26.950 --> 00:42:34.180
Number one, I think that
you, in stating what's,

00:42:34.180 --> 00:42:37.070
we talk about obstruction by
means other than filibustering,

00:42:37.070 --> 00:42:40.140
and I think that I will
caution [inaudible],

00:42:40.140 --> 00:42:42.260
any use of the word filibustering

00:42:42.260 --> 00:42:45.250
and it would make it essentially
synonymous with obstruction.

00:42:45.250 --> 00:42:48.930
And it would not include
only extended debate,

00:42:48.930 --> 00:42:53.460 position:56%
which the possibilities of which are
limited by the rules of the House.

00:42:53.460 --> 00:42:55.700
And there are other
uses of the term too.

00:42:55.700 --> 00:43:00.240
So, I wouldn't even have made
the remark about whether,

00:43:00.240 --> 00:43:02.260
what they do [inaudible]
filibustering or not.

00:43:02.260 --> 00:43:07.950
But the point about it being
obstruction stands on its own.

00:43:07.950 --> 00:43:13.680
More as a query, I
was a little surprised

00:43:13.680 --> 00:43:17.700
that in discussing
messaging tactics,

00:43:17.700 --> 00:43:23.560
you didn't include
amendment as a possibility.

00:43:23.560 --> 00:43:26.270
Certainly, putting up an
amendment, you did talk about that

00:43:26.270 --> 00:43:29.810
in effect later on in terms of,
well we'll put up this proposition

00:43:29.810 --> 00:43:36.860
that you're either going to have
to vote in favor of or look bad.

00:43:36.860 --> 00:43:38.160
That's essentially the message,

00:43:38.160 --> 00:43:39.900
the kind of activity
I would have thought.

00:43:39.900 --> 00:43:42.230
So it doesn't even come
under that category or fall

00:43:42.230 --> 00:43:43.530
under that class as well.

00:43:43.530 --> 00:43:44.830
&gt;&gt; Matthew Green: Right.

00:43:44.830 --> 00:43:47.640
So I had to be, first of all, the
first point is very well taken.

00:43:47.640 --> 00:43:50.730
And I guess I used the word
filibustering because that is sort

00:43:50.730 --> 00:43:53.250
of the understand, oh it's
the Senate doing [inaudible].

00:43:53.250 --> 00:43:55.630
But obviously, it's
more than just that.

00:43:55.630 --> 00:43:59.320
I appreciate that point
of clarification.

00:43:59.320 --> 00:44:02.290
With regards to amendments
as messaging, yes.

00:44:02.290 --> 00:44:03.910
I mean I talk about
that in the book.

00:44:03.910 --> 00:44:06.180
But I had to be careful in
creating these categories

00:44:06.180 --> 00:44:09.160
between the vehicle,
the actual thing, right.

00:44:09.160 --> 00:44:12.320
Is it an amendment or is it
a speech, and its intent.

00:44:12.320 --> 00:44:15.500
So if I put amendments
into messaging,

00:44:15.500 --> 00:44:17.480
then that I was worried
would confuse things.

00:44:17.480 --> 00:44:20.260
Because that's not the same thing
as giving a one-minute speech,

00:44:20.260 --> 00:44:21.590
which is clearly messaging.

00:44:21.590 --> 00:44:23.930
Or press conferences,
which I also talk about.

00:44:23.930 --> 00:44:27.300
But I do discuss that in the book
and in the legislating chapter,

00:44:27.300 --> 00:44:30.890
as well as in the conclusion,
that these legislating tools,

00:44:30.890 --> 00:44:36.540
whether it's amendments, motions
to recommit, discharge petitions.

00:44:36.540 --> 00:44:39.540
These have become effectively
messaging tools.

00:44:39.540 --> 00:44:43.630
So actually, for instance, I
think it was in the 2008, 2007,

00:44:43.630 --> 00:44:48.610
2008 Republicans wanted
a bill to be considered

00:44:48.610 --> 00:44:51.040
that would have eased
regulations on oil drilling.

00:44:51.040 --> 00:44:55.490
And they did at least two or three,
maybe four discharge petitions

00:44:55.490 --> 00:44:57.370
on the same bill basically.

00:44:57.370 --> 00:45:00.050
What they were doing was saying,
this is how much we care about it,

00:45:00.050 --> 00:45:01.790
and those Democrats
are bottling it up.

00:45:01.790 --> 00:45:03.210
That's a messaging tool, right.

00:45:03.210 --> 00:45:05.440
So I'm glad you raised that.

00:45:05.440 --> 00:45:06.970
But I did want to distinguish

00:45:06.970 --> 00:45:09.390
that so it didn't get
confusing for the reader.

00:45:09.390 --> 00:45:10.690
Yes sir.

00:45:10.690 --> 00:45:16.870
&gt;&gt; How prevalent was the Hastert
Rule philosophy before Hastert.

00:45:16.870 --> 00:45:23.110
&gt;&gt; Matthew Green: So before
Hastert, there was an understanding

00:45:23.110 --> 00:45:28.900
that you avoided bringing bills
to the floor that would pass

00:45:28.900 --> 00:45:31.030
because of the minority party.

00:45:31.030 --> 00:45:34.490
But it was never discussed
as an actual rule.

00:45:34.490 --> 00:45:39.420 position:56%
And so before Hastert, and certainly
before Gingrich, there were speakers

00:45:39.420 --> 00:45:42.520
who did quote/unquote
violate the Hastert Rule.

00:45:42.520 --> 00:45:44.170
Tom Foley did it, for instance,

00:45:44.170 --> 00:45:45.720
with the North American
Free Trade Agreement.

00:45:45.720 --> 00:45:48.860
The majority of Democrats voted
against it, but it still passed.

00:45:48.860 --> 00:45:55.960
And it was seen then as some kind
of vote of no confidence, right.

00:45:55.960 --> 00:45:57.510
You did it sparingly.

00:45:57.510 --> 00:46:00.650
But if it was important to you
or to the party or the country

00:46:00.650 --> 00:46:04.190
or the president, then you would do
it, and it was sort of understood.

00:46:04.190 --> 00:46:07.760
I think what's interesting now
that not only is it called a rule,

00:46:07.760 --> 00:46:10.430
which is somewhat confusing
to people,

00:46:10.430 --> 00:46:13.760
but that some Republicans have
actually wanted to make it a rule

00:46:13.760 --> 00:46:17.720
and change the House Republican
rules so that you can't do that.

00:46:17.720 --> 00:46:21.890
But I think we've seen in
recent years if you do that,

00:46:21.890 --> 00:46:24.150
that really ties the
hands of party leaders.

00:46:24.150 --> 00:46:26.430
Sometimes you just got
to get something passed.

00:46:26.430 --> 00:46:29.110
And you know your party's
not going to like it.

00:46:29.110 --> 00:46:30.550
But it's got to get done.

00:46:30.550 --> 00:46:36.520
So there's a way in which it's a
useful tool or useful technique

00:46:36.520 --> 00:46:39.730
for party leaders, albeit
one that is used sparingly.

00:46:39.730 --> 00:46:41.030
Yes.

00:46:41.030 --> 00:46:43.320 position:56%
&gt;&gt; In terms of tactics, did you look

00:46:43.320 --> 00:46:51.480
at all new [inaudible] not new
anymore, communication technologies

00:46:51.480 --> 00:46:57.680
and the ability of the minority
party develop constituencies beyond

00:46:57.680 --> 00:47:00.990
their traditional district
[inaudible].

00:47:00.990 --> 00:47:02.290
&gt;&gt; Can you repeat that?

00:47:02.290 --> 00:47:05.340 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yeah, so the question is did I
look at novel forms of communication

00:47:05.340 --> 00:47:08.750
and technology by lawmakers.

00:47:08.750 --> 00:47:10.410
Short answer is no.

00:47:10.410 --> 00:47:12.980
But it is a really
important topic actually.

00:47:12.980 --> 00:47:18.050
Because the book takes a 40-year
span, I kind of wanted to kind

00:47:18.050 --> 00:47:20.730
of control it for as
many things as possible.

00:47:20.730 --> 00:47:24.510
And at the time I started doing
this, it was still pretty new,

00:47:24.510 --> 00:47:28.020
the use of Twitter and
Facebook by the minority party.

00:47:28.020 --> 00:47:32.840
So I opted to kind of leave that
off the, you know, leave that out.

00:47:32.840 --> 00:47:35.920
Having said that though, I think
it'd be, it's a great subject,

00:47:35.920 --> 00:47:37.800
and it's clearly being used.

00:47:37.800 --> 00:47:40.330
And I would not be
surprised if the data shows

00:47:40.330 --> 00:47:42.060
that the minority party
has done it first.

00:47:42.060 --> 00:47:44.910
In fact, I, my guess would
that's absolutely right.

00:47:44.910 --> 00:47:48.680
So if you're in the minority, how
do you get the word out to people.

00:47:48.680 --> 00:47:49.980
Well, you Tweet.

00:47:49.980 --> 00:47:51.280
Oh those Democrats, look
what they did today.

00:47:51.280 --> 00:47:54.480
Oh I can't get to the floor,
blah, blah, blah, blah.

00:47:54.480 --> 00:47:58.010
And then what happens, again,
is you have innovation.

00:47:58.010 --> 00:47:59.720
And then you have replication.

00:47:59.720 --> 00:48:02.410
So the other party says oh,
well we should do that too.

00:48:02.410 --> 00:48:04.790
You do the majority in the morning,
and then they start doing it.

00:48:04.790 --> 00:48:07.050
A lot of innovation of tactics come

00:48:07.050 --> 00:48:08.740
from the minority party
in the House.

00:48:08.740 --> 00:48:10.040
Because they have fewer options.

00:48:10.040 --> 00:48:11.710 position:56%
They got to come up with new things.

00:48:11.710 --> 00:48:14.440
So I didn't look at it,
but it's really important

00:48:14.440 --> 00:48:16.500
and would be a good project.

00:48:16.500 --> 00:48:19.200
Yeah. Yes.

00:48:19.200 --> 00:48:20.500
&gt;&gt; On the motion to adjourn

00:48:20.500 --> 00:48:21.850
where you found there
had been some success,

00:48:21.850 --> 00:48:25.170
what was the mechanism for that?

00:48:25.170 --> 00:48:30.980 position:56%
And was there negotiation during the
[inaudible], or how did that happen.

00:48:30.980 --> 00:48:34.820 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Matthew Green: Yeah, because it's
aggregate, we're talking a number

00:48:34.820 --> 00:48:38.250
of cases, so I couldn't
do a case-by-case analysis

00:48:38.250 --> 00:48:39.550
to figure it out.

00:48:39.550 --> 00:48:40.850
Sometimes there were news reports

00:48:40.850 --> 00:48:42.230
where they said, you
know, this happened.

00:48:42.230 --> 00:48:44.830
A lot of it was just kind
of behind closed doors.

00:48:44.830 --> 00:48:46.180
That's why I say, inference.

00:48:46.180 --> 00:48:48.120
It's hard to know for sure.

00:48:48.120 --> 00:48:53.400
But it certainly seemed to be the
case that you would have someone

00:48:53.400 --> 00:48:56.240
in the minority complain
and do one of these motions.

00:48:56.240 --> 00:49:00.180
And especially if they kept doing
them over and over and over.

00:49:00.180 --> 00:49:03.110
And sometimes the majority would
just pull the bill from the floor

00:49:03.110 --> 00:49:04.900
and say we're done for the day.

00:49:04.900 --> 00:49:08.560 position:56%
And then the next day they would
come back and something had changed.

00:49:08.560 --> 00:49:10.490
So it certainly would
suggest there was some kind

00:49:10.490 --> 00:49:13.070
of negotiation going on.

00:49:13.070 --> 00:49:16.880
&gt;&gt; Is the speaker [inaudible]
delay [inaudible].

00:49:16.880 --> 00:49:18.180
&gt;&gt; Aha, right.

00:49:18.180 --> 00:49:21.640
So it's a privileged motion,
but the House rules also say

00:49:21.640 --> 00:49:26.120
that the speaker does not have
to entertain dilatory motions.

00:49:26.120 --> 00:49:30.500
I can't think of an example
of a speaker refusing,

00:49:30.500 --> 00:49:33.630
at least in modern era, recognizing
someone to do a motion to rise

00:49:33.630 --> 00:49:36.580
or adjourn for that purpose.

00:49:36.580 --> 00:49:41.310
Usually what happens is they
just, the Speaker just adjourns,

00:49:41.310 --> 00:49:43.250
goes into recess kind of thing.

00:49:43.250 --> 00:49:46.870
So for instance, Republicans
did this on an agriculture bill,

00:49:46.870 --> 00:49:49.080
ag spending bill in early 1990s.

00:49:49.080 --> 00:49:50.380
They were upset about
something else,

00:49:50.380 --> 00:49:55.040
but they introduced an amendment
that would cut spending by 50,

00:49:55.040 --> 00:50:00.830
I think it was $50,050, which
was exactly 1% of the budget.

00:50:00.830 --> 00:50:04.220 position:56%
And then they just got up and talked
and talked about child healthcare.

00:50:04.220 --> 00:50:05.830
And then that amendment failed.

00:50:05.830 --> 00:50:10.700
And then someone introduced an
amendment that cut $100,100.

00:50:10.700 --> 00:50:12.600
And then they just
talked more about.

00:50:12.600 --> 00:50:14.460
Now at that point I suppose
the speaker could have said,

00:50:14.460 --> 00:50:16.770
I'm not going to recognize
the next amendment.

00:50:16.770 --> 00:50:20.850
But instead they just
adjourned for the day.

